    detail:'Voiced = vocal folds vibrating; voiceless = vocal folds held open and still.',
    detailSrc:'CAI',
    examples:[
      {w:'',s:'Voiceless obstruent',e:' <span class=\"phon-ref\">/p t k f s/</span> — blocked + silent larynx'},
      {w:'',s:'Voiced obstruent',   e:' <span class=\"phon-ref\">/b d ɡ v z/</span> — blocked + vibrating larynx'},
      {w:'',s:'Voiced sonorant',    e:' <span class=\"phon-ref\">/m n l r j w/</span> — open + vibrating larynx'},
      {w:'',s:'Voiceless sonorant', e:' /h/ — open + silent larynx'},
    ],
    rules:'<span class="callout callout--warning"><strong>⚠ Author note</strong> — This card is not derived from TB or any cited source. It reflects understanding developed by the author in dialogue with Claude (Anthropic). Treat as background knowledge, not citable course content.</span><br>The <b>larynx</b> (voice box) sits at the top of the trachea in the throat. Inside it are the <b>vocal folds</b> — two muscular folds of tissue held close enough together that passing air vibrates them. That vibration is <b>voicing</b>.<br><br>The larynx and the oral cavity are two <b>independent mechanisms</b>. The oral cavity sets the <b>degree of obstruction</b> (from none = vowel, to full closure = plosive). The larynx sets <b>whether voicing occurs</b>. Neither depends on the other.<br><br>This is why sonorants are <b>almost always voiced</b> — with little oral obstruction, air moves freely through the larynx and fold vibration requires no effort. Obstruents create back-pressure that works against voicing, which is why maintaining voicing through an obstruent requires active muscular effort — and why many languages have only voiceless obstruents.',
    rulesSrc:[],
