    rules:'<span class="callout callout--warning"><strong>⚠ Author note</strong> — This card is not derived from TB or any cited source. It reflects understanding developed by the author in dialogue with Claude (Anthropic). Treat as background knowledge, not citable course content.</span><br>Sounds sit on a <b>continuum of oral constriction</b> — from completely open (vowels) to completely closed (plosives). The traditional vowel/consonant binary is a useful approximation, but the boundary is genuinely blurry.<br><br><b>Glides /j/ and /w/</b> sit closest to vowels on this continuum. /j/ is articulatorily almost identical to /iː/ — the difference is speed of movement and syllable position, not a qualitatively different constriction. /w/ similarly mirrors /uː/. They are sometimes described as <b>non-syllabic vowels</b> or <b>fast diphthong onsets</b>.<br><br><b>Syllabic consonants /n̩ l̩/</b> illustrate the limit of syllabicity as a vowel test: they carry a syllable nucleus just as vowels do, yet their oral constriction keeps them firmly in the consonant column.<br><br>The practical implication for teaching: when a student struggles with /j/ or /w/, telling them to <b>start from the vowel position</b> (/iː/ for /j/, /uː/ for /w/) and move quickly into the following vowel is both phonetically accurate and pedagogically effective.',
